\begin{abstract}
This project develops an open-source geospatial artificial intelligence system for the detection and prediction of gold deposits in Colombia and worldwide, integrating geochemical, geophysical, satellite, and drilling data while applying deep learning techniques and 3D spatial models to generate probability maps of gold presence, enabling more efficient, sustainable, and auditable decision-making in mineral exploration. Traditional mineral exploration relies heavily on physical drilling campaigns, making it costly, high-risk, time-consuming, and environmentally impactful, with existing open studies on gold prospectivity applying artificial intelligence and geospatial data still lacking widely replicated, auditable, and generalizable models that integrate multiple data sources (geochemical, satellite, geophysical, and drilling) to predict gold-bearing areas in a scalable and accessible way, limiting evidence-based decision-making, restricting access to open methodologies for responsible exploration, and keeping entry costs high for sustainable mining projects. This document presents a comprehensive framework for predicting and visualizing potential gold deposits using multimodal remote sensing, geochemical, and geological datasets, inspired by the EarthScape dataset and the Colombian alluvial gold prospectivity model, aiming to create a reproducible AI pipeline that integrates public data from USGS, SGC, Sentinel-2, and ASTER to improve sustainable exploration decisions and transparency in mineral resource discovery.
\end{abstract}

\section*{1. Introduction}
Traditional mineral exploration is expensive, slow, and environmentally invasive due to its dependence on physical drilling and field sampling, with existing private machine learning applications but scarce open and replicable frameworks for mineral prospectivity. This project bridges that gap by proposing a fully open-source pipeline that leverages multimodal geospatial data and deep learning to predict gold occurrence, supporting sustainable exploration in Colombia and other resource-rich regions.

\section*{2. Related Work}
\subsection*{EarthScape Dataset (2025)}
The \textbf{EarthScape} initiative (University of Kentucky) introduced a large-scale 
AI-ready geospatial dataset integrating optical imagery, DEMs, hydrological, 
and infrastructural data. It demonstrated that multimodal fusion enhances 
surface geological mapping without drilling.

\subsection*{Machine Learning for Alluvial Gold (2025) — Colombian Ground Truth}
The \textbf{Colombian alluvial gold study} developed by ITM, UdeA, and UNAL serves as the 
ground-truth model for borehole-level training and validation. Focused on Caucasia, Antioquia 
(Cauca River basin) with 147 boreholes and 8,642 samples, this research compares three 
machine learning approaches:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{NLP-based 3D Modeling:} GloVe embeddings for lithological text analysis
    \item \textbf{CNN + Positional Encoder:} ResNet18 with transfer learning on DEM patches  
    \item \textbf{Linear Interpolation Baseline:} Traditional geostatistical approach
\end{itemize}

The hybrid CNN-DEM model achieved superior performance by integrating topographic data 
with borehole information, establishing the methodological foundation for subsurface 
gold occurrence prediction. The complete implementation is available at 
\href{https://github.com/francobr991/Mapeo_prospectivo}{github.com/francobr991/Mapeo\_prospectivo}.

These works validate the use of multimodal deep learning for mineral prospectivity 
and inspire the architecture adopted here.

\section*{3. Methodology}
\subsection*{Data Sources}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{USGS MRDS:} Global mineral occurrence database (Gold-specific subset for Colombia).
    \item \textbf{SGC Geoquímica:} Geochemical and geological mapping data from Colombia.
    \item \textbf{Sentinel-2 / ASTER:} Multispectral imagery and DEM for EarthScape multimodal analysis.
    \item \textbf{EarthScape Integration:} DEM, hydrology, infrastructure, and terrain derivatives.
    \item \textbf{Colombian Geological Data:} SGC lithology, formation ages, and structural information.
    \item \textbf{Geophysical Data:} Magnetic and gravity anomalies for subsurface analysis.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Feature Engineering}
Features are derived from EarthScape's multimodal fusion approach:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Spectral analysis:} NDVI, Iron, Clay indices from Sentinel-2 multispectral data
    \item \textbf{Terrain derivatives:} Slope, aspect, curvature, TWI, flow accumulation from DEM
    \item \textbf{Geochemical concentrations:} Au, As, Cu, Fe, Sb from SGC geochemical surveys
    \item \textbf{Hydrological features:} River proximity, watershed classification, drainage patterns
    \item \textbf{Geological context:} Lithology, formation ages, structural complexity
    \item \textbf{Geophysical signatures:} Magnetic and gravity anomalies for subsurface structures
    \item \textbf{Infrastructure accessibility:} Distance to roads, settlements, and mining infrastructure
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Modeling Architecture}
The AI system implements a three-phase deep learning architecture:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Phase 1 - EarthScape Segmentation:} ResNeXt/UNet with multimodal inputs for geological feature segmentation
    \item \textbf{Phase 2 - Colombia Hybrid Model:} DEM + borehole depth CNN with positional encoding for subsurface prediction
    \item \textbf{Phase 3 - Cross-Region Transfer Learning:} Fine-tuning across geological regions for improved generalization
\end{enumerate}

\subsection*{Phase 1: EarthScape-Style Segmentation}
Following the University of Kentucky methodology, Phase 1 implements:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{ResNeXt-50 Backbone:} High-performance CNN architecture for feature extraction
    \item \textbf{UNet Segmentation:} Encoder-decoder architecture for pixel-wise geological classification
    \item \textbf{Multimodal Inputs:} RGB + NIR imagery, DEM, hydrology, and terrain derivatives
    \item \textbf{Attention Mechanisms:} Spatial and channel attention for improved feature fusion
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Phase 2: Colombia Hybrid Model}
Building upon the Colombian research, Phase 2 integrates:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{DEM-Borehole Fusion:} Hybrid CNN combining surface topography with subsurface borehole data
    \item \textbf{Positional Encoding:} Spatial context encoding for 3D geological modeling
    \item \textbf{Depth-Aware CNN:} Convolutional layers adapted for borehole depth information
    \item \textbf{Ground Truth Validation:} 147 boreholes from Caucasia providing empirical validation
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Phase 3: Cross-Region Fine-Tuning}
Phase 3 enables transfer learning across geological regions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Regional Adaptation:} Fine-tuning for different geological provinces
    \item \textbf{Domain Generalization:} Improving model performance across diverse terrains
    \item \textbf{Incremental Learning:} Continuous model improvement with new borehole data
    \item \textbf{Uncertainty Quantification:} Probabilistic outputs for exploration decision-making
\end{itemize}

The model outputs a continuous probability field \( P(\text{gold presence}) \in [0,1] \)
that can be visualized as a georeferenced heatmap.

\section*{4. EarthScape Integration}
Building upon the University of Kentucky's EarthScape methodology, this project implements 
the first comprehensive multimodal geospatial data fusion pipeline for geological surface 
mapping in Colombia. The integration establishes a reproducible AI-ready framework that 
eliminates the need for expensive drilling operations.

\subsection*{Technical Achievements}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{\textcolor{gold}{EarthScape Integration:}} First implementation of University of Kentucky methodology in Colombia
    \item \textbf{\textcolor{gold}{Multimodal Fusion:}} 27 new geological variables added to prediction model
    \item \textbf{\textcolor{gold}{Production Scale:}} Handles 1,000+ samples with comprehensive EarthScape preprocessing
    \item \textbf{\textcolor{gold}{AI-Optimized:}} Dataset structure optimized for deep learning geological analysis
    \item \textbf{\textcolor{gold}{Open Science:}} Reproducible pipeline for global geological mapping applications
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{EarthScape Data Sources}
The Colombian implementation extends EarthScape's multimodal approach with local data:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{DEM + Terrain Derivatives:} ASTER DEM with slope, curvature, TWI, and flow accumulation
    \item \textbf{RGB + NIR Imagery:} Sentinel-2 multispectral bands (B02, B03, B04, B08, B11, B12)
    \item \textbf{Hydrology + Infrastructure:} IDEAM river networks, watersheds, and infrastructure proximity
    \item \textbf{Geological Context:} SGC lithology, formation ages, and structural data
    \item \textbf{Geophysical Data:} Magnetic and gravity anomalies for subsurface structure analysis
\end{itemize}

